<p>
AA is certainly not a cult. It has no fees or official membership lists and no
requirements at all, other than a desire to quit drinking. The 12 steps are
suggested only. No one lives in a compound, is required to give money or allegiance
or to believe anything. AA is actually the quintessential democratic American
institution.

<p>
You seem to have much knowledge of AA, yet you don't seem to know these most basic
facts about AA. And you have a real resentment against Buchman. You are probably a
jealous, hateful, destructive and deceptive Jew &#8212; that is my best guess. But then
you could  be a crazed atheist, or maybe just an insecure mainstream Christian. But
my best estimate is that you are the type of Jew as described above. Am I right?

<p>
Wayne S.

<p>
<font color="blue">
Hello Wayne,
<p>
Thanks for the letter. Your denial of the cult characteristics of A.A. doesn't
hold much water.
<p>
<ul>
<li> The defining characteristics of a cult are not whether members
pay dues or whether there is an official membership list. Whether a cult is money-grubbing
is only one of a hundred common cult characteristics in
<a href="orange-cult.html" target="_blank">The Cult Test</a>, and an official
membership list isn't a cult characteristic at all.

<p><li>
The Twelve Steps are not just &quot;suggestions&quot;. That is one of the standard A.A.
bait-and-switch tricks:
<a href="orange-bait-switch.html#suggested" target="_blank">First, they will tell you that the Twelve Steps are
only <i>suggested</i> as a program of recovery, but then you hear
the slogan &quot;Work The Steps Or Die&quot;.</a>

<p>
Also, <a href="orange-bait-switch.html#take_what2" target="_blank">First, they will tell you that
you can <i>&quot;Take what you want, and leave the rest.&quot;</i>
Then they will tell you that you must follow the formula exactly, or else
it won't work.</a>

<p><li> You don't have to live in a compound to be in a cult. Most cults do not have
isolated compounds. Members of Scientology, the Moonies, the Jehovah's Witnesses, and
Amway are all free to come and go as they chose (or are ordered to), but they are still
in a cult.

<p><li>
Alcoholics Anonymous most assuredly requires that people believe things.
<b>&quot;[We] Came to believe&quot;</b>
is the start of Step Two, isn't it? The claim that A.A. requires no beliefs is just
another one of Bill Wilson's lies, a recruiting deception,
and it's some more standard A.A. bait-and-switch tricks:
<ul>
<p><li> <a href="orange-bait-switch.html#shifting_objectives" target="_blank">Shifting objectives:
First the goal is to quit drinking, and then the goal is to
&quot;acquire faith&quot; and &quot;come to believe&quot;
in Bill Wilson's religion.</a>

<p><li> <a href="orange-bait-switch.html#believe_everything" target="_blank">First, A.A. tells you that
&quot;A.A. requires no beliefs,&quot; but then you have to believe
everything they tell you, and have blind faith in the proclamations
of Bill Wilson.</a>
</ul>

<p><li>
This claim is really over the edge:
<font color="black">
&quot;AA is actually the quintessential democratic American institution.&quot;</font><br>
Heaven help us if America has sunk so low.

<p><li>
Yes, I have a &quot;real resentment&quot; against
<a href="orange-rroot060.html" target="_blank">Frank Buchman</a>.
He was a very evil and dishonest man who did a lot of harm to a lot of people.
America still has not entirely recovered from what he did,
or gotten rid of his lies. Heck, you still live some of them, don't you?

<p><li>
Finally, I must thank you for revealing your soul to us, and clearly showing us
your A.A. &quot;spirituality&quot;:

<p>
<blockquote>
<font color="black" face="Lucida,Utopia bold,Utopia,Helvetica,Charter,Arial,sans-serif,Sans Serif,New Century Schoolbook">
You are probably a jealous, hateful, destructive and deceptive Jew
&#8212; that is my best guess. But then
you could  be a crazed atheist, or maybe just an insecure mainstream Christian. But
